title: Civcraft: Day 2
author: Marcus_Flaminius
pages:
#-         ~~~~~~~~
§l       Civcraft§r:

§l       Day Two§r
        ~~~~~~~~





§o             by§r

      tkrandomness


#- 
  The moon still shone above me when I left the safety of the building/farm. I could no longer wait with nothing to do. I wondered if someone would one day return to where I just left.
  Not far from the building I discovered trees planted in a 


#- patch. I was happy to finally find some for I could now build and survive on my own if need be. I cut down two and took with me some saplings.
  With a new-found map of the world, I began heading North-East where it hinted at civilization. The first 



#- sign of it was a massive wall. After crossing the empty plains, I arrived at a structure bigger than I had ever expected to exist. It was stone and extended for quite some distance.
  After walking along it for a short time, I found a whole in it 



#- which I could slip through. Behind the wall I found a farm of pumpkins, many ready to be harvested. I looked around, but there was no one. I ignored the pumpkins and continued walking through the farms. There were more plots, the building fit 



#- many.
  On the other side was the other wall, but more importantly there were potatoes. Finally, I could eat. After eating a few, I replanted for either the owners or the next starved man to come across them.
  I wandered around the farm for a while, 

#- trying to
 find the way back out. Eventually, I found it but fell in pain in doing so. No matter, with food I can heal. I traveled past another enclosed farm, this one looked mostly harvested. Further on my trail I found my forest natural forest, 


#- a jungle.
  I felt it was best to just walk through on my quest rather than explore for now. I could come back to harvest the wood another time.
  I found a small path at the end of the forest and followed it. I began to hear what sounded like the 


#- voices of others 
talking. The next thing I found was another wall. Bigger then even the last, it extended all along the horizon. I had arrived at the gates of the Common- wealth.






